Document: Exporting for Dedicated Servers
Path: godot/tutorials/export/exporting_for_dedicated_servers.rst
Summary: This document explains how to export Godot projects for dedicated servers.

Exporting for Dedicated Servers

This page explains how to export Godot projects for dedicated servers.

Dedicated servers are a common way to host multiplayer games. They run the game logic without any graphical interface, making them more efficient and stable. Godot provides built-in support for exporting dedicated server builds.

Exporting a dedicated server build involves a few steps:

1.  **Enable Dedicated Server Export:** In the Project Settings, under the "Export" tab, you'll find an option to enable dedicated server export. This will create a new export preset specifically for dedicated servers.

2.  **Configure Export Preset:** Once enabled, you can configure the dedicated server export preset like any other export preset. This includes choosing the target platform, architecture, and other relevant settings.

3.  **Build the Server:** After configuring the preset, you can build the dedicated server executable by clicking the "Export Project" button in the Project Manager.

The resulting executable will be a headless version of your game, suitable for running on a server. You can then use this executable with your game's networking code to host multiplayer sessions.

Key Rule: Dedicated server builds do not include the game's rendering or input systems, making them lighter and more performant for server-side logic.

When developing for dedicated servers, it's important to ensure that your game logic is independent of any graphical elements. This means avoiding direct manipulation of nodes that are only relevant for the client, such as `Camera` or `Sprite3D` nodes, unless they are specifically used for server-side visualization or debugging.

GDScript:
```gdscript
# Example of server-side logic
extends Node

var players = {}

func _ready():
    # Start a network server or connect to an existing one
    pass

func _on_player_connected(player_id):
    players[player_id] = {}
    print("Player connected: ", player_id)

func _on_player_disconnected(player_id):
    if players.has(player_id):
        players.erase(player_id)
        print("Player disconnected: ", player_id)

func _process(delta):
    # Update game state, process player inputs, etc.
    pass
```

C#:
```csharp
// Example of server-side logic
using Godot;
using System;
using System.Collections.Generic;

public class GameServer : Node
{
    private Dictionary<int, object> players = new Dictionary<int, object>();

    public override void _Ready()
    {
        // Start a network server or connect to an existing one
    }

    public void OnPlayerConnected(int playerId)
    {
        players[playerId] = new object(); // Placeholder for player data
        GD.Print($"Player connected: {playerId}");
    }

    public void OnPlayerDisconnected(int playerId)
    {
        if (players.ContainsKey(playerId))
        {
            players.Remove(playerId);
            GD.Print($"Player disconnected: {playerId}");
        }
    }

    public override void _Process(float delta)
    {
        // Update game state, process player inputs, etc.
    }
}
```
